@incollection{Cabej2012,
abstract = {The process of individual development from a single cell, an egg cell or a zygote, to an adult organism is known as ontogeny. It represents the first laboratory for antenatally testing new developmental solutions and evolutionary changes before they are put through the sieve of natural selection under natural conditions. This chapter presents an argument that the developmental pathways of both, ontogeny, and phylotopic stage converge into a common set of homologous properties, representing the members of a systematic group, i.e., to a common Bauplan. The systematic correlation of three events (the Bauplan, the exhaustion of parental epigenetic information, and the formation of the operative embryonic central nervous system) in the early vertebrate ontogeny suggests that a causal relationship between them might exist. Following this, the study presents another argument to provide an understanding of the fact that ontogeny may undergo a change without any changes occurring in the genes. Many organisms undergo adaptive responses to significant changes in environment, or even in the absence of changes in environment, produce offspring of more than one morphotype, omit certain embryonic stages, and even undergo the so-called reverse ontogeny, which certainly requires new structural information. This chapter then deals with the generation of epigenetic information for organogenesis after the phylotypic stage and stress-induced developmental instability and evolution. It concludes by highlighting certain developmental constraints and adaptive evolutionary innovations.},
